## Migration: `Thread.Abort` → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Pattern Identified

**Timeout enforcement** — `Thread.Abort()` forcibly kills a thread after a deadline. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (`SYSLIB0006`). You must switch to cooperative cancellation.

### Why This Breaks

| Removed API | .NET 8 Behavior |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` is long-running, you must make it cooperate

The critical paradigm shift: **cancellation is cooperative now**. The `Func<T>` must check the token, otherwise it keeps running in the background after timeout. Change the signature:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller must check the token:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Fix |
|---|---|
| **Work keeps running after timeout** | The old `Abort()` killed the thread. `Cancel()` only sets a flag — `work` must call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular checkpoints. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers. Always `using var cts = ...`. |
| **Blocking calls ignore the token** | `Thread.Sleep(ms)` won't wake up. Use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` instead. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Let it propagate; only catch at the orchestration point (as shown above). |
| **Truly uncooperative code** (can't modify `work`) | Move it to a child **process** and use `Process.Kill()` — that's the only .NET 8 equivalent of a hard abort. |

### Async version (preferred if callers are async)

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```
